WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.000
Are any of you people, members of the World Future Society?

00:10.640 --> 00:13.400
I'm sure most of you heard about the C. Clark.

00:13.400 --> 00:15.280
Will you raise your hands?

00:15.280 --> 00:16.780
Good.

00:16.780 --> 00:21.880
He said that if he wrote a book that everybody enjoyed

00:21.880 --> 00:27.120
and understood, he said he wouldn't be saying anything new.

00:27.120 --> 00:29.000
Think about that.

00:29.040 --> 00:32.380
What I'm going to talk about is going to change some of your

00:32.380 --> 00:35.880
lives, the way you look at yourself and the way you look

00:35.880 --> 00:37.680
at the world around you.

00:37.680 --> 00:42.580
The subject matter is not the kind of matter to get from

00:42.580 --> 00:45.160
ordinary sources or books.

00:45.160 --> 00:49.760
So I would like your participation in an experiment.

00:49.760 --> 00:54.560
And some of you might be able to tell what it is that I draw

00:54.560 --> 00:57.300
on the board before I finish.

00:57.340 --> 01:00.000
And if you know what it is, interrupt.

01:00.000 --> 01:01.340
Say, I got it.

01:01.340 --> 01:02.820
So I'm going to start.

01:02.820 --> 01:04.900
Can all of you see the board?

01:04.900 --> 01:06.740
I don't think I can make it with this.

01:12.100 --> 01:13.860
Can all of you see the board?

01:13.860 --> 01:15.860
Can you hear me all right?

01:15.860 --> 01:17.500
OK.

01:17.500 --> 01:19.900
The minute you know what it is, interrupt.

01:28.300 --> 01:31.260
The same thinking ship, the Titanic.

01:31.260 --> 01:31.860
What is it?

01:31.860 --> 01:32.500
Titanic.

01:32.500 --> 01:33.780
OK, great.

01:33.780 --> 01:37.260
Now, if he didn't call that, remember, there's no ship

01:37.260 --> 01:38.860
there at all.

01:38.860 --> 01:43.860
There was enough bits for his associative memory to put that

01:43.860 --> 01:44.700
together.

01:44.700 --> 01:46.820
Now, you know that's not a ship.

01:46.820 --> 01:47.980
Now, what is this?

01:47.980 --> 01:50.060
Some of you older people might guess this.

01:53.500 --> 01:55.060
An alarm clock.

01:55.060 --> 01:56.780
Who did that?

01:56.780 --> 02:00.140
You are amazing.

02:00.140 --> 02:01.500
Where's the alarm clock?

02:01.500 --> 02:06.860
Well, anyway, if she wasn't able to call that, I would have

02:06.860 --> 02:10.220
put the legs on it and the clock and Hamilton watch

02:10.220 --> 02:12.740
coming, until somebody called it.

02:12.740 --> 02:17.180
Now, there are still some that cannot see the ship.

02:17.180 --> 02:20.420
So I would have gone all along, put all the windows in,

02:20.420 --> 02:22.940
Titanic, everything, until somebody got up and said,

02:22.940 --> 02:24.740
yeah, Titanic.

02:24.740 --> 02:31.700
Well, this is an attempt to prove that all of us are

02:31.700 --> 02:36.860
capable of making decisions and arriving at a conclusion

02:36.860 --> 02:40.540
without all of the information prepared for us.

02:40.540 --> 02:43.860
That is a unique quality in human beings.

02:43.860 --> 02:48.100
We can put things together, and we do not require the

02:48.100 --> 02:50.980
accumulation of a great deal of information.

02:50.980 --> 02:53.220
In this system, if you understand this

02:53.220 --> 02:56.660
quite well, who would you say this is?

03:13.340 --> 03:16.060
Who said that?

03:16.060 --> 03:18.220
Who said that?

03:18.220 --> 03:20.540
Lincoln.

03:20.580 --> 03:22.260
I don't see Lincoln, but it's Lincoln.

03:22.260 --> 03:24.060
It would have been Abraham Lincoln.

03:24.060 --> 03:26.820
When I got filled with it, I would have gone on with a beard

03:26.820 --> 03:28.780
and all of the stuff.

03:28.780 --> 03:32.500
So this is just to prove that people can put something

03:32.500 --> 03:36.940
together, and I'm going to try to explain to you just what

03:36.940 --> 03:40.500
creative thinking really is.

03:40.500 --> 03:43.860
Now, I'm going to use old language, the language that I

03:43.860 --> 03:47.100
use with people who are not familiar with this way of

03:47.100 --> 03:48.020
thinking.

03:48.020 --> 03:53.460
The old language is that people can think and reason.

03:53.460 --> 03:56.060
I do not believe that is possible.

03:56.060 --> 03:57.900
I have many inventions.

03:57.900 --> 04:00.740
I've worked on many different things, but I don't believe

04:00.740 --> 04:04.260
that human beings can think or reason.

04:04.260 --> 04:05.740
This is what I do believe.

04:05.740 --> 04:08.140
By the way, you don't have to accept anything I say.

04:08.140 --> 04:11.380
During the question period, don't be polite.

04:11.380 --> 04:13.220
Come at it from all angles.

04:13.220 --> 04:14.820
Break it down if you can.

04:14.820 --> 04:17.580
This helps me, and it helps you.

04:17.620 --> 04:21.020
So when I talk about thinking and reasoning and putting

04:21.020 --> 04:25.100
things together, we're talking about the forces that shape

04:25.100 --> 04:26.900
human behavior.

04:26.900 --> 04:34.460
I believe that all human behavior is lawful, that the

04:34.460 --> 04:38.100
reactions and values that all people have are perfectly

04:38.100 --> 04:41.060
lawful to the environment that they come from.

04:41.060 --> 04:45.860
So every human being is perfectly well adjusted from

04:45.860 --> 04:48.860
where they are coming from, from their background and

04:48.860 --> 04:49.940
experience.

04:49.940 --> 04:54.060
If you as a baby were raised by the Seminole Indians, you

04:54.060 --> 04:56.500
would behave if you never saw anything else like a

04:56.500 --> 04:58.180
Seminole Indian.

04:58.180 --> 05:01.060
And if you were brought up in any other Indian group and you

05:01.060 --> 05:04.900
had feathers in your head, in your head gear, and you were

05:04.900 --> 05:07.780
dancing around the fire, and I walked over and said, that's

05:07.780 --> 05:08.300
ridiculous.

05:08.300 --> 05:11.060
What are you dancing around the fire with the feathers for?

05:11.060 --> 05:12.780
You don't take your hat, throw it on the ground, says

05:12.780 --> 05:13.060
you don't.

05:13.060 --> 05:14.860
I never thought of it that way.

05:14.860 --> 05:16.180
We can't do that.

05:16.180 --> 05:18.940
We're victims of culture.

05:18.940 --> 05:22.380
We look at the world with our background.

05:22.380 --> 05:24.620
We have no other way of doing it.

05:24.620 --> 05:28.820
Psychology is kind of a rudimentary form today, an

05:28.820 --> 05:32.900
attempt to grasp at the factors that shape human

05:32.900 --> 05:36.140
behavior, the factors that are responsible for the way we

05:36.140 --> 05:40.140
look at ourselves, other people, and the way we behave, or

05:40.140 --> 05:42.100
if you wish, misbehave.

05:42.140 --> 05:45.540
I don't believe that any human being misbehaves.

05:45.540 --> 05:49.460
They use whatever tools they know of, whatever tools

05:49.460 --> 05:51.100
they're familiar with.

05:51.100 --> 05:53.780
Language is a tool.

05:53.780 --> 05:57.860
It's someone to show you a picture of an airplane, what

05:57.860 --> 06:00.700
appeared to be an airplane, without wings.

06:00.700 --> 06:03.460
When people look at it and they stand by and they say, it

06:03.460 --> 06:04.700
will never fly.

06:04.700 --> 06:06.940
But they don't say, how do you propose to lift off the

06:06.940 --> 06:08.820
ground without wings?

06:08.820 --> 06:12.020
That's the key to communication.

06:12.060 --> 06:17.140
Now, a very famous scientist deceased now, trying to get

06:17.140 --> 06:20.820
the government and people to put up sufficient funds to

06:20.820 --> 06:25.900
monitor outer space, to try to make contact with extra

06:25.900 --> 06:28.220
terrestrial life.

06:28.220 --> 06:31.460
I want to try to save this to you and think about what I

06:31.460 --> 06:32.900
say, toss it around.

06:32.900 --> 06:35.740
I'm using the old language because you're not that

06:35.740 --> 06:39.540
familiar with these values.

06:39.540 --> 06:44.340
If people or beings or things can travel 100 million

06:44.340 --> 06:50.780
light years through time and space, they are not humanoid.

06:50.780 --> 06:55.700
The storage system for water would occupy miles.

06:55.700 --> 06:59.500
And all of the facilities required by humans would

06:59.500 --> 07:02.820
take up tremendous amounts of space and require

07:02.820 --> 07:05.660
tremendous amounts of energy.

07:05.660 --> 07:07.300
Now, there are people that talk of flying

07:07.300 --> 07:10.100
saucers at the land here on Earth.

07:10.100 --> 07:13.540
And they go to some farmer, and they take him into the

07:13.540 --> 07:17.140
saucer, and they do all kinds of experiments on them.

07:17.140 --> 07:21.500
Now, first of all, people do not travel hundreds of

07:21.500 --> 07:25.500
millions of light years to pick up some farmer and ask him

07:25.500 --> 07:26.940
what kind of suspenders he wears.

07:30.500 --> 07:33.340
Carl Sagan wanted to communicate with extra

07:33.340 --> 07:34.380
terrestrials.

07:34.380 --> 07:38.060
He hoped that they, in turn, would communicate with us.

07:38.060 --> 07:41.300
Now, you know that the Republicans can't communicate

07:41.300 --> 07:43.620
with the Democrats.

07:43.620 --> 07:46.820
You know that husbands and wives have difficulty in

07:46.820 --> 07:48.020
communicating.

07:48.020 --> 07:51.020
Children and parents have difficulty, because the

07:51.020 --> 07:55.460
language we use was designed a long time ago.

07:55.460 --> 08:01.460
And it is inherently difficult to get ideas across in the

08:01.460 --> 08:03.980
language that we use today.

08:03.980 --> 08:08.260
However, when engineers meet and talk, they speak a

08:08.260 --> 08:10.460
different language.

08:10.460 --> 08:13.220
One engineer might present a very thin cable, and says,

08:13.220 --> 08:17.980
this can support 5,000 tons.

08:17.980 --> 08:21.180
And the other engineer says, what's its tensile strength?

08:21.180 --> 08:22.860
And he's given that information.

08:22.860 --> 08:24.580
Then he puts it in a machine.

08:24.580 --> 08:25.860
I don't know whether he knew this.

08:25.860 --> 08:30.180
And he snaps it to make sure that it holds for that.

08:30.220 --> 08:42.620
When engineers design an airplane, they do all the

08:42.620 --> 08:43.940
calculations.

08:43.940 --> 08:46.700
This is a very rapid drawing of a

08:46.700 --> 08:48.740
front view of an airplane.

08:48.740 --> 08:51.660
They do all the rapid calculations, and they figure

08:51.660 --> 08:54.860
what that wing will be able to support.

08:54.860 --> 08:57.340
And after all their calculations, and after

08:57.340 --> 09:02.020
they're certain, they then pile sandbags on the wing.

09:02.020 --> 09:03.060
Did you know that?

09:03.060 --> 09:09.500
Until it breaks off to make damn sure that it does the job.

09:09.500 --> 09:12.900
Now, that does not exist in everyday language.

09:12.900 --> 09:15.900
In everyday language, you don't have that ability.

09:15.900 --> 09:18.580
When an engineer meets another engineer, he says, I can

09:18.580 --> 09:23.620
illuminate an area with this tiny point of light that has

09:23.620 --> 09:26.140
50,000 square feet.

09:26.180 --> 09:27.940
The engineer says, well, that's not possible.

09:27.940 --> 09:29.820
He doesn't talk like that.

09:29.820 --> 09:32.940
He says, how do you power that unit?

09:32.940 --> 09:35.460
What kind of voltage does it take?

09:35.460 --> 09:37.780
How do you illuminate that spot?

09:37.780 --> 09:39.220
They ask questions.

09:39.220 --> 09:42.900
The average person, yeah, nah, not in a thousand years.

09:42.900 --> 09:44.940
That's been around for a long time.

09:44.940 --> 09:50.060
That is a language of war, of hatred, of bigotry, of

09:50.060 --> 09:54.500
prejudice, the inability to ask questions.

09:54.500 --> 09:57.540
And we've got to be very careful about that.

09:57.540 --> 10:00.940
And at one lecture I remember at Princeton, I was trying to

10:00.940 --> 10:05.300
say that human beings cannot think or reason, because of

10:05.300 --> 10:08.540
psychology, department, and sociology.

10:08.540 --> 10:11.540
Well, one of the individuals stood up, one of the staff,

10:11.540 --> 10:14.780
and he said, all right, where did the camera come from?

10:14.780 --> 10:16.780
There were no cameras at one time.

10:16.780 --> 10:19.540
Someone had to think about a camera.

10:19.540 --> 10:21.900
He just doesn't come out of the thin air.

10:21.900 --> 10:26.860
And after doing a lot of work, many years ago, in ancient

10:26.860 --> 10:30.060
Egypt, or if you live out in the country, or have lived

10:30.060 --> 10:33.980
out in the country, if there was a hole in the barn wall,

10:33.980 --> 10:38.900
that is, a knot was knocked out, the cows on the outside

10:38.900 --> 10:42.820
appeared on the wall of the barn, upside down.

10:42.820 --> 10:47.380
And in Egypt, you went in this dome to see the upside down

10:47.380 --> 10:48.420
world.

10:48.420 --> 10:51.780
There was a little hole here, and the daylight came in, and

10:51.780 --> 10:54.740
you saw people walking upside down on the wall.

10:54.740 --> 10:57.260
How many of you have experienced that kind of

10:57.260 --> 10:59.300
phenomenon?

10:59.300 --> 11:02.260
That is essentially the box-hole camera.

11:02.260 --> 11:05.380
A camera, the simple camera without a lens, there's just

11:05.380 --> 11:07.540
a little hole in the box.

11:07.540 --> 11:12.220
And somebody said, well, how can I see that image?

11:12.220 --> 11:15.340
And they used a transparent membrane back here, and they

11:15.340 --> 11:20.500
could see the upside down head, or a person, or a cow.

11:20.540 --> 11:24.420
And they asked this question, if only I can retain that

11:24.420 --> 11:25.340
image?

11:25.340 --> 11:26.780
Well, that isn't the answer.

11:26.780 --> 11:28.100
That's just a question.

11:28.100 --> 11:31.380
I wonder how I could retain that image.

11:31.380 --> 11:35.980
So years before that, the American Indians and other

11:35.980 --> 11:41.460
primitives have taken tappercloth, or they'd weave

11:41.460 --> 11:44.700
natural materials into a kind of a fabric.

11:44.700 --> 11:47.220
And then they would take berry juices and

11:47.220 --> 11:48.980
dye it different colors.

11:48.980 --> 11:53.620
Sometimes a leaf would fall upon that surface, and after

11:53.620 --> 11:57.580
the sun dried it, they had an image of the leaf.

11:57.580 --> 12:03.500
So they began to use dyes from this background, that all

12:03.500 --> 12:08.620
human beings, to understand the better, the first human

12:08.620 --> 12:12.580
being that jumped off a precipice with wings, he

12:12.580 --> 12:13.700
died.

12:13.740 --> 12:17.300
And his brother-in-law wrote, next time, make the wings

12:17.300 --> 12:19.660
larger.

12:19.660 --> 12:23.940
No one starts out right away and solves a problem, unless

12:23.940 --> 12:26.740
you have a tremendous background in many different

12:26.740 --> 12:27.820
areas.

12:27.820 --> 12:30.580
Well, the next guy that jumped off, he jumped off of the

12:30.580 --> 12:31.820
larger wings.

12:31.820 --> 12:34.700
And he flew a little, and then they went, and the old

12:34.700 --> 12:38.020
fisherman said, you've got to brace them wings, like a

12:38.020 --> 12:40.020
boat, like a man.

12:40.020 --> 12:42.780
They're not going to hold, so they braced it.

12:42.780 --> 12:45.740
And then they jumped off the precipice, this individual,

12:45.740 --> 12:49.060
and he flew, and he hit a tree.

12:49.060 --> 12:51.740
And he hurt his leg real badly.

12:51.740 --> 12:54.220
And his wife said, you know, John, a fish has a

12:54.220 --> 12:57.820
rudder, good point.

12:57.820 --> 13:00.660
And they stuck the rudder on the airplane.

13:00.660 --> 13:04.780
No one ever sat down and invented a television set, an

13:04.780 --> 13:08.940
airplane, the electric light, wireless, none of that came

13:08.940 --> 13:12.740
about by men walking in deep concentration.

13:12.740 --> 13:16.900
And then, through some ethereal substance, bingo, the

13:16.900 --> 13:18.300
idea is formulated.

13:18.300 --> 13:20.140
It doesn't work that way.

13:20.140 --> 13:22.540
It's hard work.

13:22.540 --> 13:25.820
And I make more mistakes than anybody I know, because I

13:25.820 --> 13:27.020
try more things.

13:29.740 --> 13:32.980
There's nothing wrong with building something, and

13:32.980 --> 13:34.940
finding out that it doesn't work.

13:34.940 --> 13:37.100
This is where you get your experience.

13:37.100 --> 13:39.500
There's nothing wrong with criticism.

13:39.500 --> 13:41.980
I remember the first model airplanes that I built went

13:41.980 --> 13:45.460
nosing into the ground, and I was ashamed of them.

13:45.460 --> 13:49.700
And a young engineer told me that my center of gravity had

13:49.700 --> 13:50.300
to be corrected.

13:50.300 --> 13:53.140
That is, move the wing forward.

13:53.140 --> 13:59.020
And so all of us stand on the shoulders of one another, and

13:59.020 --> 14:00.780
we shape the future.

14:00.780 --> 14:03.620
Another question that was asked, well, somebody had to

14:03.620 --> 14:04.940
invent the bow and arrow.

14:04.940 --> 14:06.420
Somebody had to think of it.

14:06.420 --> 14:08.500
It just didn't come out of nowhere.

14:08.500 --> 14:12.420
Well, I talked to many Indians, and after talking to many

14:12.420 --> 14:17.620
Indians, this is when I found out that Indians used to skin

14:17.620 --> 14:21.060
animals, and this is a lousy drawing of the skin of an

14:21.060 --> 14:25.340
animal stretched out in the sun.

14:25.340 --> 14:29.380
When the Indians got back, the skin was half the size.

14:29.380 --> 14:31.340
It shrunk and became thicker.

14:31.340 --> 14:33.100
And they didn't like that at all.

14:33.100 --> 14:37.660
So they cut leather into strips, thin strips.

14:37.660 --> 14:41.980
And they took an existing frame, and they tied that skin

14:41.980 --> 14:42.780
to the frame.

14:42.780 --> 14:45.860
Something you may have seen this, was lace of leather,

14:45.860 --> 14:48.500
all in one, to prevent it from shrinking.

14:48.500 --> 14:51.500
But when they cut the strips of leather and put them out in

14:51.500 --> 14:54.740
the sun, they shrunk and became fat and short.

14:54.740 --> 14:57.220
And they were just pleased with that.

14:57.220 --> 15:01.540
After many, many years, one Indian tied that strand of

15:01.540 --> 15:06.900
leather to a piece of wood, a stick.

15:06.900 --> 15:09.900
He split the top, tied it up, and tied the leather to the

15:09.900 --> 15:10.500
stick.

15:10.500 --> 15:14.860
When he came back, hoping that it would dry and not shrink,

15:14.860 --> 15:16.900
the stick took this form.

15:16.900 --> 15:20.180
It was bent.

15:20.180 --> 15:23.780
He plucked that in and went, bong, now.

15:23.780 --> 15:26.940
And after many years, somebody took another piece of wood,

15:26.940 --> 15:30.380
put it in and pulled the string, and off it went.

15:30.460 --> 15:33.460
Well, if man can't think or reason, where did the movie

15:33.460 --> 15:35.460
camera come from?

15:35.460 --> 15:36.500
Somebody had to think of that.

15:36.500 --> 15:38.100
It doesn't exist out there.

15:38.100 --> 15:40.220
Well, here's where it came from.

15:40.220 --> 15:44.620
Many, many years ago, thousands of years ago in China,

15:44.620 --> 15:50.380
they used to take a candle, and they'd take some bamboo

15:50.380 --> 15:53.460
paper at the time, and put it in front of the candle.

15:53.460 --> 15:55.820
And then they'd cut out a little figurine of a human

15:55.820 --> 15:58.220
being, and put the candle behind it.

15:58.220 --> 16:02.060
And as the candle undulated, the little person would dance,

16:02.060 --> 16:03.380
and they'd play music.

16:03.380 --> 16:05.020
That was the beginning.

16:05.020 --> 16:06.300
How did that happen?

16:06.300 --> 16:09.540
Some guy had a candle in the piece of paper, and he was

16:09.540 --> 16:12.700
just happened to be behind it, and his finger appeared to

16:12.700 --> 16:14.260
move on the screen.

16:14.260 --> 16:18.460
And so he extracted or built upon that phenomena.

16:18.460 --> 16:21.460
Then later, there's something interesting occurring.

16:21.460 --> 16:25.980
The Chinese used to take these tremendous scrolls and

16:25.980 --> 16:26.860
open them up.

16:26.860 --> 16:31.100
Well, they then later taped, or they wired, or they used

16:31.100 --> 16:35.300
gut and tied many pages together and built a kind of a

16:35.300 --> 16:36.260
pad.

16:36.260 --> 16:41.340
But in order to get to a particular page, the oriental

16:41.340 --> 16:45.300
would mark the corner of the page so that they can find

16:45.300 --> 16:46.580
with a symbol.

16:46.580 --> 16:49.980
And as you flip through the pages fast, that little dot

16:49.980 --> 16:52.220
would jump all over the place.

16:52.220 --> 16:57.220
Well, years later, an individual drew various

16:57.220 --> 17:01.540
successive pictures of a bird in flight, and put them down

17:01.540 --> 17:03.940
in the corner of the paper and flipped it.

17:03.940 --> 17:06.740
And the little bird wings began to move up and down.

17:06.740 --> 17:11.980
Well, a Frenchman saw that, and he took little pieces of

17:11.980 --> 17:17.220
cardboard, and he put them in a circular pattern.

17:17.220 --> 17:20.700
I'm going to try to get it down as quickly as I can.

17:20.700 --> 17:24.740
And he put a crank up here that you turn, and the little

17:24.740 --> 17:27.180
pictures would go around in a circle.

17:27.180 --> 17:30.020
And the Chinese had something like this also, and they had

17:30.020 --> 17:33.220
a bamboo interrupter that would just hold the picture for

17:33.220 --> 17:36.420
a few seconds, a second, less than a second, as you turned

17:36.420 --> 17:39.460
it, a man appeared to move across the screen.

